node.text: We all love those all white leaves on our variegated Monsteras and Syngoniums, etc, but we need to perform some maintenance on some of our variegated plants! All white leaves will not last forever, and in this video, I teach you how to prune your variegated plants to encourage more balanced variegated growth.

🌱Many people have asked me how to minimize rotting for water propagated leaf segments of snake plants. 
🌱The two keys that I’ve found are to:
.

1️⃣Make your cuttings and allow the segments to dry for 2-3 days or so. This allows the cut end to callous over and helps to minimize rotting.
.

2️⃣Change the water as frequently as needed to keep it fresh and clean, and also gently rub off any slime that forms on the cuttings. I do this under running water. Especially for new cuttings, check on them 2-3 days a week and clean them as needed!
.
🌱#houseplantwarrior @detroitcityplants has had success once she followed these tips.  I’m glad you had success with this Julie!
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
💦Misting does not increase humidity. It only wets your leaves. If you overdo misting, it can also help encourage fungal issues.
💦Use a humidifier instead if your goal is to increase humidity. Don’t forget to also provide some air circulation, especially if you have a lot of plants in the room. 
💦Misting IS helpful in some other ways:
1️⃣It helps to discourage spider mites.
2️⃣You can mist foliage and then wipe dust off to keep leaves clean.
3️⃣Epiphytes love to be misted because they absorb water that way. 
.
.

node.text:
🪴This Cast Iron Plant has a story, and often times, it is the story that makes the plant extra special. 
🪴When my grandmother came to Italy in 1968, she took a piece of a cast iron plant (from her town’s medieval church) with her to the U.S.  Growing up in Ohio, I always remembered seeing this plant in her house. When I bought my first home, she divided her plant and gave me a piece...and it was probably about 17 or 18 years ago. She has since passed, but it is a constant reminder of her and the town my family is from. 🙏🏻
🪴Do you have any special plants with stories?  Cast Iron Plants are wonderful, lower light plants that can take a beating and are pretty underrated in my opinion! There are some beautiful variegated varieties, but I love my plain green plant 💚
.
.
.
.
.

💦When you’re diluting a fertilizer with water, it is important to always read the label and measure both the fertilizer and water amounts correctly.
💦Never eyeball any amounts. If your solution turns out too weak, this is not an issue, but if it’s too concentrated, you are at risk of fertilizer burn. 
💦So measure away! I like to use dedicated kitchen measuring spoons that I only use for fertilizing, and I use a gallon jug to measure water. This way I know I have the correct concentration. 
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
🪴String of Pearls enjoyings its best life outdoors 🥰 Anytime you are moving a houseplant from indoors to outdoors, always move it into complete shade first (even for sun loving plants like this). They need to slowly become accustomed to the higher light outdoors. Once in shade for a while, you can start to slowly increase any direct sun exposure. Moving indoor plants straight into full sun outside will quickly cause them to scald (often in a matter of hours). Slowly but surely is the way to go. 
🪴Has anyone ever burned a plant this way? I’ve seen a lot of people do this and not know what happened, so this is your public service announcement 😊📣📢 I elaborate on this topic in my book coming out this March! 📚 
.
.
.
.
.
